       full-width vertically here, so — unlike the desktop fan, where cards sit
       side-by-side and the spark slides horizontally — there's no horizontal movement
       to speak of; every card starts at the same left edge. `left` stays fixed at the
       same offset O1's own card always used (the analytic --spark-left the script still
       computes is desktop-fan-only math and must not leak in here). `top` instead
       tracks --spark-top, the active card's own offsetTop plus the numeral offset, so
       the spark slides down/up to sit beside whichever card is currently centered while
       scrolling. The `4.04rem` fallback matches O1's own desktop value at rest — the
       correct default before any scroll/JS has run (O1 is the first card, offsetTop 0). */
    .programs-row .o1-spark {
      left: -4.23rem;
      top: var(--spark-top, 4.04rem);
      transition: top 250ms ease;
    }
    /* `.programs-row .card` (two classes) rather than repeating `.card--o1, .card--o2, …`
       (one class each): `.card.is-active` now sets width too (hover-to-expand width fix,
       above) at two-class specificity — O1 keeps `.is-active` at every viewport (nothing
       ever removes it below 1024, since the hover script no-ops there), so a one-class
       override here would lose to `.card.is-active`'s width regardless of source order.
       Matching its specificity and relying on this block being declared later restores
       the correct full-width override for every card, active or not. */
    .programs-row .card {
      width: 100%;
      margin-left: 0;
      min-height: auto;
      /* Full-width cards: the %-notch would balloon (37% of a full-width O4) — restore
